					<div id=3D"mw-content-text" class=3D"mw-body-content"><div class=3D"mw=
-content-ltr mw-parser-output" lang=3D"en" dir=3D"ltr"><div class=3D"shortd=
escription nomobile noexcerpt noprint searchaux" style=3D"display:none">Dis=
tinction between mass and weight</div>
<figure class=3D"mw-halign-right" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Mass_versus_weight_in_earth_and_mars.svg" cla=
ss=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikiped=
ia/commons/thumb/8/83/Mass_versus_weight_in_earth_and_mars.svg/330px-Mass_v=
ersus_weight_in_earth_and_mars.svg.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"300" he=
ight=3D"293" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"744" data-file-he=
ight=3D"726"></a><figcaption>Mass and weight of a given object on <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Earth" title=3D"Earth">Earth</a> and <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mars" title=3D"Mars">Mars</a>. Weight =
varies due to different amount of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Gravitational_acceleration" title=3D"Gravitational acceleration">gravitatio=
nal acceleration</a> whereas mass stays the same.</figcaption></figure>
<p>In common usage, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mass" titl=
e=3D"Mass">mass</a> of an object is often referred to as its <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Weight" title=3D"Weight">weight</a>, though thes=
e are in fact different concepts and quantities. Nevertheless, one object w=
ill always weigh more than another with less mass if both are subject to th=
e same gravity (i.e. the same <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Grav=
itational_field" title=3D"Gravitational field">gravitational field</a> stre=
ngth).
</p><p>In scientific contexts, mass is the amount of "<a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Matter" title=3D"Matter">matter</a>" in an object (thou=
gh "matter" may be difficult to define), but weight is the <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Force" title=3D"Force">force</a> exerted on an obj=
ect's matter by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gravitation" class=
=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Gravitation">gravity</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-1" c=
lass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mass_versus_wei=
ght#cite_note-1"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">]</span></a></sup> At the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Earth" title=3D"Earth">Earth</a>'s surface, an object whose mass is exactl=
y one <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kilogram" title=3D"Kilogram"=
>kilogram</a> weighs approximately 9.81 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Newton_(unit)" title=3D"Newton (unit)">newtons</a>, the product of it=
s mass and the gravitational field strength there. The object's weight is l=
ess on <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mars" title=3D"Mars">Mars</=
a>, where gravity is weaker; more on <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Saturn" title=3D"Saturn">Saturn</a>, where gravity is stronger; and very=
 small in space, far from significant sources of gravity, but it always has=
 the same mass.
</p><p>Material objects at the surface of the Earth have weight despite suc=
h sometimes being difficult to measure. An object floating freely on water,=
 for example, does not appear to have weight since it is buoyed by the wate=
r. But its weight can be measured if it is added to water in a container wh=
ich is entirely supported by and weighed on a scale. Thus, the "weightless =
object" floating in water actually transfers its weight to the bottom of th=
e container (where the pressure increases). Similarly, a balloon has mass b=
ut may appear to have no weight or even negative weight, due to <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Buoyancy" title=3D"Buoyancy">buoyancy</a> in =
air. However the weight of the balloon and the gas inside it has merely bee=
n transferred to a large area of the Earth's surface, making the weight dif=
ficult to measure. The weight of a flying airplane is similarly distributed=
 to the ground, but does not disappear. If the airplane is in level flight,=
 the same weight-force is distributed to the surface of the Earth as when t=
he plane was on the runway, but spread over a larger area.
</p><p>A better scientific definition of mass is its description as being a=
 measure of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Inertia" title=3D"Iner=
tia">inertia</a>, which is the tendency of an object to not change its curr=
ent state of motion (to remain at constant velocity) unless acted on by an =
external unbalanced force. Gravitational "weight" is the force created when=
 a mass is acted upon by a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gravita=
tion" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Gravitation">gravitational field</a> a=
nd the object is not allowed to free-fall, but is supported or retarded by =
a mechanical force, such as the surface of a planet. Such a force constitut=
es weight.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Mass_versus_weight#cite_note-2"><span class=3D"cite-brac=
ket">[</span>2<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> This force ca=
n be added to by any other kind of force.
</p><p>While the <i>weight</i> of an object varies in proportion to the str=
ength of the gravitational field, its <i>mass</i> is constant, as long as n=
o energy or matter is added to the object.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-3" class=3D"r=
eference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mass_versus_weight#cite_=
note-3"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>3<span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
]</span></a></sup> For example, although a satellite in orbit (essentially =
a free-fall) is "weightless", it still retains its mass and inertia. Accord=
ingly, even in orbit, an astronaut trying to accelerate the satellite in an=
y direction is still required to exert force, and needs to exert ten times =
as much force to accelerate a 10=E2=80=91ton satellite at the same rate as =
one with a mass of only 1&nbsp;ton.
</p>
<meta property=3D"mw:PageProp/toc">
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Overview">Overview</h2><spa=
n class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DMass_versus_weight&a=
mp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D1" title=3D"Edit section: Overview"><span>ed=
it</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<figure typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/F=
ile:8ball_break.jpg" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://uplo=
ad.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e4/8ball_break.jpg/330px-8ball_b=
reak.jpg" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"300" height=3D"200" class=3D"mw-file-=
element" data-file-width=3D"2310" data-file-height=3D"1540"></a><figcaption=
>Matter's mass strongly influences many familiar kinetic properties, such a=
s the motion of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Billiard_ball" tit=
le=3D"Billiard ball">billiard balls</a>.</figcaption></figure>
<p>Mass is (among other properties) an <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Inertia" title=3D"Inertia">inertial</a></i> property; that is, the =
tendency of an object to remain at constant velocity unless acted upon by a=
n outside <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Force" title=3D"Force">f=
orce</a>. Under <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Isaac_Newton" titl=
e=3D"Isaac Newton">Sir Isaac Newton's</a> <span class=3D"currentage"></span=
>338-year-old <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Newton%27s_laws_of_m=
otion" title=3D"Newton's laws of motion">laws of motion</a> and an importan=
t formula that sprang from his work, <span class=3D"nowrap"><i>F</i> =3D=E2=
=80=89<i>ma</i>,</span> an object with a mass, <i>m</i>, of one <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kilogram" title=3D"Kilogram">kilogram</a> <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Acceleration" title=3D"Acceleration">=
accelerates</a>, <i>a</i>, at one <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Metre_per_second_squared" title=3D"Metre per second squared">meter per seco=
nd per second</a> (about one-tenth the acceleration due to <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Earth%27s_gravity" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"=
Earth's gravity">Earth's gravity</a>)<sup id=3D"cite_ref-4" class=3D"refere=
nce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mass_versus_weight#cite_note-=
4"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</sp=
an></a></sup> when acted upon by a force, <i>F</i>, of one <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Newton_(unit)" title=3D"Newton (unit)">newton</a>.
</p><p>Inertia is seen when a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bowl=
ing_ball" title=3D"Bowling ball">bowling ball</a> is pushed horizontally on=
 a level, smooth surface, and continues in horizontal motion. This is quite=
 distinct from its weight, which is the downwards gravitational force of th=
e bowling ball one must counter when holding it off the floor. The weight o=
f the bowling ball on the Moon would be one-sixth of that on the Earth, alt=
hough its mass remains unchanged. Consequently, whenever the physics of <i>=
recoil kinetics</i> (mass, velocity, inertia, <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Inelastic_collision" title=3D"Inelastic collision">inelastic</a=
> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elastic_collision" title=3D"=
Elastic collision">elastic collisions</a>) dominate and the influence of gr=
avity is a negligible factor, the behavior of objects remains consistent ev=
en where gravity is relatively weak. For instance, billiard balls on a bill=
iard table would scatter and recoil with the same speeds and energies after=
 a break shot on the Moon as on Earth; they would, however, drop into the p=
ockets much more slowly.<sup class=3D"noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact=
" style=3D"white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title=3D"Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span titl=
e=3D"This claim needs references to reliable sources. (February 2025)">cita=
tion needed</span></a></i>]</sup>
</p><p>In the physical sciences, the terms "mass" and "weight" are rigidly =
defined as separate measures, as they are different physical properties. In=
 everyday use, as all everyday objects have both mass and weight and one is=
 almost exactly proportional to the other, "weight" often serves to describ=
e both properties, its meaning being dependent upon context. For example, i=
n retail commerce, the "net weight" of products actually refers to mass, an=
d is expressed in mass units such as grams or ounces (see also <i><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pound_(mass)#Use_in_commerce" title=3D"Po=
und (mass)">Pound: Use in commerce</a>)</i>. Conversely, the <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tire_code" title=3D"Tire code">load index</a> ra=
ting on automobile tires, which specifies the maximum <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Structural_load" title=3D"Structural load">structural l=
oad</a> for a tire in kilograms, refers to weight; that is, the force due t=
o gravity. Before the late 20th century, the distinction between the two wa=
s not strictly applied in technical writing, so that expressions such as "m=
olecular weight" (for <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Molecular_ma=
ss" title=3D"Molecular mass">molecular mass</a>) are still seen.<sup class=
=3D"noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" style=3D"white-space:nowrap;">[<=
i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title=
=3D"Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title=3D"This claim needs references t=
o reliable sources. (February 2025)">citation needed</span></a></i>]</sup>
</p><p>Because mass and weight are separate quantities, they have different=
 units of measure. In the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internat=
ional_System_of_Units" title=3D"International System of Units">Internationa=
l System of Units</a> (SI), the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ki=
logram" title=3D"Kilogram">kilogram</a> is the basic unit of mass, and the =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Newton_(unit)" title=3D"Newton (un=
it)">newton</a> is the basic unit of force. The non-SI <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kilogram-force" title=3D"Kilogram-force">kilogram-forc=
e</a> is also a unit of force typically used in the measure of weight. Simi=
larly, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Avoirdupois" title=3D"A=
voirdupois">avoirdupois</a> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pound_=
(mass)" title=3D"Pound (mass)">pound</a>, used in both the <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Imperial_system" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Im=
perial system">Imperial system</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/United_States_customary_units" title=3D"United States customary units"=
>U.S. customary units</a>, is a unit of mass, and its related unit of force=
 is the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pound-force" class=3D"mw-r=
edirect" title=3D"Pound-force">pound-force</a>.<sup class=3D"noprint Inline=
-Template Template-Fact" style=3D"white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title=3D"Wikipedia:Cita=
tion needed"><span title=3D"This claim needs references to reliable sources=
. (February 2025)">citation needed</span></a></i>]</sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Converting_units_of_mass_to=
_equivalent_forces_on_Earth">Converting units of mass to equivalent forces =
on Earth</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-b=
racket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DMas=
s_versus_weight&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D2" title=3D"Edit section: C=
onverting units of mass to equivalent forces on Earth"><span>edit</span></a=
><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<figure typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/F=
ile:Southern_ocean_gravity_hg.png" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=
=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a9/Southern_ocea=
n_gravity_hg.png/330px-Southern_ocean_gravity_hg.png" decoding=3D"async" wi=
dth=3D"260" height=3D"181" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"115=
5" data-file-height=3D"806"></a><figcaption>Gravity anomalies covering the =
Southern Ocean are shown here in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/F=
alse-color" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"False-color">false-color</a> rel=
ief. This image has been normalized to remove variation due to differences =
in latitude.</figcaption></figure>
<p>When an object's weight (its gravitational force) is expressed in "kilog=
rams", this actually refers to the kilogram-force (kgf or kg-f), also known=
 as the <i>kilopond</i> (kp), which is a non-SI unit of force. All objects =
on the Earth's surface are subject to a gravitational acceleration of appro=
ximately 9.8&nbsp;m/s<sup>2</sup>. The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/General_Conference_on_Weights_and_Measures" title=3D"General Conferenc=
e on Weights and Measures">General Conference on Weights and Measures</a> f=
ixed the value of standard gravity at precisely 9.80665&nbsp;m/s<sup>2</sup=
> so that disciplines such as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Metr=
ology" title=3D"Metrology">metrology</a> would have a standard value for co=
nverting units of defined mass into defined forces and <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pressure" title=3D"Pressure">pressures</a>. Thus the k=
ilogram-force is defined as precisely 9.80665 newtons. In reality, gravitat=
ional acceleration (symbol: <i>g</i>) varies slightly with <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Latitude" title=3D"Latitude">latitude</a>, <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elevation" title=3D"Elevation">elevation<=
/a> and subsurface density; these variations are typically only a few tenth=
s of a percent. See also <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gravim=
etry" title=3D"Gravimetry">Gravimetry</a></i>.<sup class=3D"noprint Inline-=
Template Template-Fact" style=3D"white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title=3D"Wikipedia:Citat=
ion needed"><span title=3D"This claim needs references to reliable sources.=
 (February 2025)">citation needed</span></a></i>]</sup>
</p><p>Engineers and scientists understand the distinctions between mass, f=
orce, and weight. Engineers in disciplines involving <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Weight" title=3D"Weight">weight</a> <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Structural_load" title=3D"Structural load">loading</a>=
 (force on a structure due to gravity), such as <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Structural_engineering" title=3D"Structural engineering">stru=
ctural engineering</a>, convert the mass of objects like concrete and autom=
obiles (expressed in kilograms) to a force in newtons (by multiplying by so=
me factor around 9.8; 2 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Significan=
t_figures" title=3D"Significant figures">significant figures</a> is usually=
 sufficient for such calculations) to derive the load of the object. Materi=
al properties like <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elastic_modulus=
" title=3D"Elastic modulus">elastic modulus</a> are measured and published =
in terms of the newton and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pascal_=
(unit)" title=3D"Pascal (unit)">pascal</a> (a unit of pressure related to t=
he newton).<sup class=3D"noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" style=3D"wh=
ite-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:C=
itation_needed" title=3D"Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title=3D"This cla=
im needs references to reliable sources. (February 2025)">citation needed</=
span></a></i>]</sup>
</p>
<div style=3D"clear:both;" class=3D""></div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Buoyancy_and_weight">Buoyan=
cy and weight</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsect=
ion-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=
=3DMass_versus_weight&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D3" title=3D"Edit sect=
ion: Buoyancy and weight"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsectio=
n-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<figure typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/F=
ile:Submerged-and-Displacing.svg" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D=
"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/6a/Submerged-and-Di=
splacing.svg/250px-Submerged-and-Displacing.svg.png" decoding=3D"async" wid=
th=3D"174" height=3D"273" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"175"=
 data-file-height=3D"275"></a><figcaption>Regardless of the <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fluid" title=3D"Fluid">fluid</a> in which an obje=
ct is immersed (gas or liquid), the buoyant force on an object is equal to =
the weight of the fluid it displaces.</figcaption></figure>
<figure class=3D"mw-halign-left" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Hot_air_balloon_just_above_the_ground.jpg" cla=
ss=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikiped=
ia/commons/thumb/4/4c/Hot_air_balloon_just_above_the_ground.jpg/330px-Hot_a=
ir_balloon_just_above_the_ground.jpg" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"255" heig=
ht=3D"302" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"1298" data-file-hei=
ght=3D"1536"></a><figcaption>A hot air balloon when it has <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Neutral_buoyancy" title=3D"Neutral buoyancy">neutr=
al buoyancy</a> has no weight for the men to support but still retains grea=
t inertia due to its mass.</figcaption></figure>
<p>Usually, the relationship between mass and weight on Earth is highly pro=
portional; objects that are a hundred times more massive than a one-liter b=
ottle of soda almost always weigh a hundred times more=E2=80=94approximatel=
y 1,000 newtons, which is the weight one would expect on Earth from an obje=
ct with a mass slightly greater than 100 kilograms. Yet, this is not always=
 the case and there are familiar objects that violate this <span class=3D"n=
owrap">mass=E2=80=89/=E2=80=89weight</span> proportionality.<sup class=3D"n=
oprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" style=3D"white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title=3D"W=
ikipedia:Citation needed"><span title=3D"This claim needs references to rel=
iable sources. (February 2025)">citation needed</span></a></i>]</sup>
</p><p>A common helium-filled toy balloon is something familiar to many. Wh=
en such a balloon is fully filled with helium, it has <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Buoyancy" title=3D"Buoyancy">buoyancy</a>=E2=80=94a for=
ce that opposes gravity. When a toy balloon becomes partially deflated, it =
often becomes <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Neutral_buoyancy" ti=
tle=3D"Neutral buoyancy">neutrally buoyant</a> and can float about the hous=
e a meter or two off the floor. In such a state, there are moments when the=
 balloon is neither rising nor falling and=E2=80=94in the sense that a scal=
e placed under it has no force applied to it=E2=80=94is, in a sense perfect=
ly weightless (actually as noted below, weight has merely been redistribute=
d along the Earth's surface so it cannot be measured). Though the rubber co=
mprising the balloon has a mass of only a few grams, which might be almost =
unnoticeable, the rubber still retains all its mass when inflated.<sup clas=
s=3D"noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" style=3D"white-space:nowrap;">[=
<i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" titl=
e=3D"Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title=3D"This claim needs references =
to reliable sources. (February 2025)">citation needed</span></a></i>]</sup>
</p><p>Again, unlike the effect that low-gravity environments have on weigh=
t, buoyancy does not make a portion of an object's weight vanish; the missi=
ng weight is instead being borne by the ground, which leaves less force (we=
ight) being applied to any scale theoretically placed underneath the object=
 in question (though one may perhaps have some trouble with the practical a=
spects of accurately weighing something individually in that condition). If=
 one were however to weigh a small wading pool that someone then entered an=
d began floating in, they would find that the full weight of the person was=
 being borne by the pool and, ultimately, the scale underneath the pool. Wh=
ereas a buoyant object (on a properly working scale for weighing buoyant ob=
jects) would weigh less, the <i>object<span style=3D"margin-left:0.2em">/<s=
pan style=3D"margin-left:0.2em">fluid system</span></span></i> becomes heav=
ier by the value of object's full mass once the object is added. Since air =
is a fluid, this principle applies to object<span style=3D"margin-left:0.2e=
m">/<span style=3D"margin-left:0.2em">air</span></span> systems as well; la=
rge volumes of air=E2=80=94and ultimately the ground=E2=80=94supports the w=
eight a body loses through mid-air buoyancy.<sup class=3D"noprint Inline-Te=
mplate Template-Fact" style=3D"white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title=3D"Wikipedia:Citatio=
n needed"><span title=3D"This claim needs references to reliable sources. (=
February 2025)">citation needed</span></a></i>]</sup>
</p><p>The effects of buoyancy do not just affect balloons; both liquids an=
d gases are <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fluid" title=3D"Fluid"=
>fluids</a> in the physical sciences, and when all macro=E2=80=91size objec=
ts larger than dust particles are immersed in fluids on Earth, they have so=
me degree of buoyancy.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-5" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mass_versus_weight#cite_note-5"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>5<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> =
In the case of either a swimmer floating in a pool or a balloon floating in=
 air, buoyancy can fully counter the gravitational weight of the object bei=
ng weighed, for a weighing device in the pool. However, as noted, an object=
 supported by a fluid is fundamentally no different from an object supporte=
d by a sling or cable=E2=80=94the weight has merely been transferred to ano=
ther location, not made to disappear.
</p><p>The mass of "weightless" (neutrally buoyant) balloons can be better =
appreciated with much larger hot air balloons. Although no effort is requir=
ed to counter their weight when they are hovering over the ground (when the=
y can often be within one hundred newtons of zero weight), the inertia asso=
ciated with their appreciable mass of several hundred kilograms or more can=
 knock fully grown men off their feet when the balloon's basket is moving h=
orizontally over the ground.<sup class=3D"noprint Inline-Template Template-=
Fact" style=3D"white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title=3D"Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span =
title=3D"This claim needs references to reliable sources. (February 2025)">=
citation needed</span></a></i>]</sup>
</p><p>Buoyancy and the resultant reduction in the downward force of object=
s being weighed underlies <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Archimed=
es%27_principle" title=3D"Archimedes' principle">Archimedes' principle</a>,=
 which states that the buoyancy force is equal to the weight of the fluid t=
hat the object displaces. If this fluid is air, the force may be small.<sup=
 class=3D"noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" style=3D"white-space:nowra=
p;">[<i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed"=
 title=3D"Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title=3D"This claim needs refere=
nces to reliable sources. (February 2025)">citation needed</span></a></i>]<=
/sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Buoyancy_effects_of_air_on_=
measurement">Buoyancy effects of air on measurement</h2><span class=3D"mw-e=
ditsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DMass_versus_weight&amp;action=3Dedi=
t&amp;section=3D4" title=3D"Edit section: Buoyancy effects of air on measur=
ement"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span>=
</span></div>
<p>Normally, the effect of air buoyancy on objects of normal <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Density" title=3D"Density">density</a> is too sm=
all to be of any consequence in day-to-day activities.  For instance, buoya=
ncy's diminishing effect upon one's body weight (a relatively low-density o=
bject) is <span class=3D"frac"><span class=3D"num">1</span>=E2=81=84<span c=
lass=3D"den">860</span></span> that of gravity (for pure water it is about =
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1154941027"><span class=3D"frac"><span class=3D"num">1</span>=E2=81=84<span=
 class=3D"den">770</span></span> that of gravity). Furthermore, <i>variatio=
ns</i> in barometric pressure rarely affect a person's weight more than =C2=
=B11 part in 30,000.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-6" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mass_versus_weight#cite_note-6"><span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">[</span>6<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> How=
ever, in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Metrology" title=3D"Metro=
logy">metrology</a> (the science of measurement), the precision mass standa=
rds for calibrating laboratory scales and balances are manufactured with su=
ch accuracy that air density is accounted for to compensate for buoyancy ef=
fects. Given the extremely high cost of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Platinum-iridium_alloy" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Platinum-iridi=
um alloy">platinum-iridium</a> mass standards like the <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/International_prototype_of_the_kilogram" class=3D"mw-r=
edirect" title=3D"International prototype of the kilogram">international pr=
ototype of the kilogram</a> (<i>the</i> mass standard in France that define=
d the magnitude of the kilogram), high-quality "working" standards are made=
 of special <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stainless_steel" title=
=3D"Stainless steel">stainless steel</a> alloys<sup id=3D"cite_ref-7" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mass_versus_weight#=
cite_note-7"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>7<span class=3D"cite-brac=
ket">]</span></a></sup> with densities of about 8,000&nbsp;kg/m<sup>3</sup>=
, which occupy greater volume than those made of platinum-iridium, which ha=
ve a density of about 21,550&nbsp;kg/m<sup>3</sup>. For convenience, a stan=
dard value of buoyancy relative to stainless steel was developed for metrol=
ogy work and this results in the term "conventional mass".<sup id=3D"cite_r=
ef-8" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mass_ver=
sus_weight#cite_note-8"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>8<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Conventional mass is defined as follow=
s: "For a mass at 20&nbsp;=C2=B0C, 'conventional mass' is the mass of a ref=
erence standard of density 8,000&nbsp;kg/m<sup>3</sup> which it balances in=
 air with a density of 1.2&nbsp;kg/m<sup>3</sup>." The effect is a small on=
e, 150&nbsp;<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Parts_per_million" cla=
ss=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Parts per million">ppm</a> for stainless steel =
mass standards, but the appropriate corrections are made during the manufac=
ture of all precision mass standards so they have the true labeled mass.
</p><p>Whenever a high-precision scale (or balance) in routine laboratory u=
se is calibrated using stainless steel standards, the scale is actually bei=
ng calibrated to conventional mass; that is, true mass minus 150&nbsp;ppm o=
f buoyancy. Since objects with precisely the same mass but with different d=
ensities displace different volumes and therefore have different buoyancies=
 and weights, any object measured on this scale (compared to a stainless st=
eel mass standard) has <i>its</i> conventional mass measured; that is, its =
true mass minus an <i>unknown</i> degree of buoyancy. In high-accuracy work=
, the volume of the article can be measured to mathematically null the effe=
ct of buoyancy.
</p>
<div style=3D"clear:both;" class=3D""></div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Types_of_scales_and_what_th=
ey_measure">Types of scales and what they measure</h2><span class=3D"mw-edi=
tsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DMass_versus_weight&amp;action=3Dedit&=
amp;section=3D5" title=3D"Edit section: Types of scales and what they measu=
re"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></s=
pan></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-halign-left" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Balance_%C3%A0_tabac_1850.JPG" class=3D"mw-fil=
e-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/t=
humb/1/17/Balance_%C3%A0_tabac_1850.JPG/250px-Balance_%C3%A0_tabac_1850.JPG=
" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"203" height=3D"190" class=3D"mw-file-element"=
 data-file-width=3D"960" data-file-height=3D"899"></a><figcaption>A balance=
-type weighing scale: Unaffected by the strength of gravity.</figcaption></=
figure>
<figure typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/F=
ile:Bathroomscales.jpg" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://u=
pload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d7/Bathroomscales.jpg/250px-B=
athroomscales.jpg" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"190" class=3D=
"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"441" data-file-height=3D"336"></a><fig=
caption>Load-cell based bathroom scale: Affected by the strength of gravity=
.</figcaption></figure>
<p>When one stands on a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Weighing_s=
cale#Balance" title=3D"Weighing scale">balance-beam</a>-type <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Weighing_scale" title=3D"Weighing scale">scale</=
a> at a doctor's office, they are having their mass measured directly. This=
 is because balances ("dual-pan" mass comparators) compare the gravitationa=
l force exerted on the person on the platform with that on the sliding coun=
terweights on the beams; gravity is the force-generating mechanism that all=
ows the needle to diverge from the "balanced" (null) point. These balances =
could be moved from Earth's equator to the poles and give exactly the same =
measurement, i.e. they would not spuriously indicate that the doctor's pati=
ent became 0.3% heavier; they are immune to the gravity-countering <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Centrifugal_force" title=3D"Centrifugal f=
orce">centrifugal force</a> due to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Earth%27s_rotation" title=3D"Earth's rotation">Earth's rotation</a> about =
its axis. But if one steps onto spring-based or digital <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Load_cell" title=3D"Load cell">load cell</a>-based sc=
ales (single-pan devices), one is having one's weight (gravitational force)=
 measured; and variations in the strength of the gravitational field affect=
 the reading. In practice, when such scales are used in commerce or hospita=
ls, they are often adjusted on-site and certified on that basis, so that th=
e mass they measure, expressed in pounds or kilograms, is at the desired le=
vel of accuracy.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-9" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mass_versus_weight#cite_note-9"><span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">[</span>9<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div style=3D"clear:both;" class=3D""></div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Use_in_United_States_commer=
ce">Use in United States commerce</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/w/index.php?title=3DMass_versus_weight&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D6"=
 title=3D"Edit section: Use in United States commerce"><span>edit</span></a=
><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>In the United States of America the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/United_States_Department_of_Commerce" title=3D"United States Departmen=
t of Commerce">United States Department of Commerce</a>, the <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Technology_Administration" title=3D"Technology A=
dministration">Technology Administration</a>, and the <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/National_Institute_of_Standards_and_Technology" title=
=3D"National Institute of Standards and Technology">National Institute of S=
tandards and Technology</a> (NIST) have defined the use of mass and weight =
in the exchange of goods under the Uniform Laws and Regulations in the area=
s of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Metrology" title=3D"Metrology=
">legal metrology</a> and engine fuel quality in <a rel=3D"nofollow" class=
=3D"external text" href=3D"https://www.nist.gov/publications/uniform-laws-a=
nd-regulations-areas-legal-metrology-and-fuel-quality-3">NIST Handbook 130<=
/a>:
</p>
<blockquote>
<p><b>K. "Mass" and "Weight"</b> [See Section K. NOTE]
</p><p>The mass of an object is a measure of the object's inertial property=
, or the amount of matter it contains. The weight of an object is a measure=
 of the force exerted on the object by gravity, or the force needed to supp=
ort it. The pull of gravity on the earth gives an object a downward acceler=
ation of about 9.8&nbsp;m/s<sup>2</sup>. In trade and commerce and everyday=
 use, the term "weight" is often used as a synonym for "mass". The "net mas=
s" or "net weight" declared on a label indicates that the package contains =
a specific amount of commodity exclusive of wrapping materials. The use of =
the term "mass" is predominant throughout the world, and is becoming increa=
singly common in the United States.<br>
(Added 1993)
</p><p><i><b>Section K. NOTE:</b></i> When used in this law (or regulation)=
, the term "weight" means "mass". (see paragraphs K. "Mass" and "Weight" an=
d L. Use of the Terms "Mass" and "Weight" in Section&nbsp;I. Introduction o=
f NIST Handbook 130 for an explanation of these terms.)<br>
(Note Added 1993)
</p><p><b>L. Use of the Terms "Mass" and "Weight"</b> [See Section K. NOTE]
</p><p>When used in this handbook, the term "weight" means "mass". The term=
 "weight" appears when inch-pound units are cited, or when both inch-pound =
and SI units are included in a requirement. The terms "mass" or "masses" ar=
e used when only SI units are cited in a requirement. The following note ap=
pears where the term "weight" is first used in a law or regulation.
</p>
</blockquote>
<p>U.S. federal law, which supersedes this handbook, also defines weight, p=
articularly Net Weight, in terms of the avoirdupois pound or mass pound. Fr=
om <a rel=3D"nofollow" class=3D"external text" href=3D"https://www.govinfo.=
gov/app/details/CFR-2016-title21-vol2/CFR-2016-title21-vol2-sec101-105">21 =
CFR =C2=A7 101.105&nbsp;=E2=80=93  Declaration of net quantity of contents =
when exempt</a>:
</p>
<blockquote>
<p>(a) The principal display panel of a food in package form shall bear a d=
eclaration of the net quantity of contents. This shall be expressed in the =
terms of weight, measure, numerical count, or a combination of numerical co=
unt and weight or measure. The statement shall be in terms of fluid measure=
 if the food is liquid, or in terms of weight if the food is solid, semisol=
id, or viscous, or a mixture of solid and liquid; except that such statemen=
t may be in terms of dry measure if the food is a fresh fruit, fresh vegeta=
ble, or other dry commodity that is customarily sold by dry measure. If the=
re is a firmly established general consumer usage and trade custom of decla=
ring the contents of a liquid by weight, or a solid, semisolid, or viscous =
product by fluid measure, it may be used. Whenever the Commissioner determi=
nes that an existing practice of declaring net quantity of contents by weig=
ht, measure, numerical count, or a combination in the case of a specific pa=
ckaged food does not facilitate value comparisons by consumers and offers o=
pportunity for consumer confusion, he will by regulation designate the appr=
opriate term or terms to be used for such commodity.
</p><p>(b)(1) Statements of weight shall be in terms of avoirdupois pound a=
nd ounce.
</p>
</blockquote>
<p>See also <a rel=3D"nofollow" class=3D"external text" href=3D"https://www=
.govinfo.gov/app/details/CFR-2024-title21-vol4/CFR-2024-title21-vol4-sec201=
-51">21 CFR =C2=A7 201.51 =E2=80=93 Declaration of net quantity of contents=
</a> for general labeling and prescription labeling requirements.
</p>
